&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dispersion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of Total Internal Reflection&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;div&gt;Sparkling of Diamond&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;div&gt;Optical Fibre Communication&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;div&gt;Formation of Mirage&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When white light is passed through a glass prism it splits into its spectrum of colors (in order violet, indigo, blue, green, yellow, orange, and red) and this process of white light splitting into its constituent colors is termed as &lt;strong&gt;dispersion&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Total internal reflection (TIR):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When a wave travels from a denser medium to a rarer medium,&lt;strong&gt; it bends away from the normal and as the angle of incidence increases in the denser medium&lt;/strong&gt;, the angle of refraction in the rarer medium also increases and at a certain angle the angle of refraction becomes 90&amp;deg;. The angle of incidence is called the &lt;strong&gt;critical angle (C)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When the angle of incidence becomes greater than the critical angle, the light ray returns to the same medium after reflection from the interface. This phenomenon is called&lt;strong&gt; total internal reflection (TIR)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;width: 350px;&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;speed of light&lt;/strong&gt; in a vacuum is approximately &lt;strong&gt;299,792 kilometers per second&lt;/strong&gt; (km/s), or about &lt;strong&gt;3.00 x 10&lt;sup&gt;8&lt;/sup&gt; meters per second (m/s)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This speed is a fundamental constant of nature and is denoted by the letter &lt;strong&gt;c&lt;/strong&gt; in physics equations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The speed of light plays a crucial role in areas of physics, including in the theory of relativity proposed by Albert Einstein.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Nothing can travel faster than the speed of light in a vacuum, according to current scientific understanding.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;concept of the speed of light&lt;/strong&gt; has been explored since ancient times, but accurate measurement became possible only in the 17th and 18th centuries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The first known practical measurement of the speed of light was made by Ole R&amp;oslash;mer in 1676, based on observations of Jupiter&amp;#39;s moons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the early 20th century, Albert Einstein&amp;#39;s theory of special relativity established that the speed of light in a vacuum is the same for all observers, regardless of their relative motion or the motion of the light source.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The speed of light is not only a key element of physics but also has practical applications in technology, including in telecommunications and GPS systems.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span data-darkreader-inline-color=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41); --darkreader-inline-color: #d1cdc7;&quot;&gt;at the centre of the curvature.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span data-darkreader-inline-color=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41); --darkreader-inline-color: #d1cdc7;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Position of the Object at the Centre of Curvature:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
When an object is placed at the center of curvature (C) of a concave mirror, the object is essentially at a distance equal to the radius of curvature from the mirror&amp;#39;s pole.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Formation of Image:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this scenario, the reflected rays from the object converge and meet at the center of curvature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The image formed is real because the reflected rays actually converge at a point.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The image is inverted because the reflected rays cross over at the center of curvature, resulting in an inverted orientation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The image is of the same size as the object because the distance from the object to the mirror is the same as the distance from the image to the mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If an object is placed at the &lt;strong&gt;centre of curvature of a concave mirror, then the image formed is real, inverted, and of the same size as that of the object.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/qImage653f49253eee7d32d0c88c32.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Virtual, Erect&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The image formed by a convex mirror is always &lt;strong&gt;Virtual and Erect&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Convex mirror&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If the outer surface of the spherical mirror is the reflecting surface then it is called a convex mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It is also called the diverging mirror.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The nature of the image formed by a convex mirror does not depend on the distance of the object from the mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The images are always virtual,&lt;/strong&gt; smaller than the object, and situated behind the mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The convex mirror always forms a virtual image that lies between the pole and the focus of the mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A virtual image is always erect. &lt;/strong&gt;The convex mirror always forms an image that is smaller than the size of the object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Convex mirrors are widely used as rear-view mirrors in automobiles and vehicles because they can diverge light beams and make virtual images.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concave lens&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concave lens&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An air bubble in water behaves as a concave lens&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A parallel beam of light passing through it, is diverged or spread out.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Concave lens is also called as diverging lens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concave mirror&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is one of the spherical mirrors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reflection of light occurs at its concave surface, is called a concave mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These mirrors magnify the object placed close to them.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Convex lens&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A beam of light passing through it, is converged to a point.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Convex lens is also called as converging lens.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Convex mirror&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is one of the spherical mirrors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reflection of light occurs at its convex surface, is called a convex mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The image formed by these mirrors is smaller than the object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Rear viewing mirrors used in vehicles is the most common convex mirrors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plane mirror&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Plane mirror is a mirror with a flat reflective surface.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Plane mirror makes an Image of objects in front of it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;shy;The image is virtual, upright and laterally inverted.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
